                    </div>
                    <span>I watched this when it was on PBS last month and thought it was one of the best documentaries I've seen.  It left me wondering what happened to politicians like RFK.  Why are we consistently stuck with less than stellar candidates for the most important job in the world? </span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Superb documentary on a great man</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>6</span>
                      /
                      <span>6</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2004-10-21</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>As an admirer of Robert Kennedy, I was really looking forward to seeing this new PBS documentary on him and I was not disappointed.
<br />
<br />From the emotional start (at the 1964 Democratic Convention where RFK made a heartfelt speech about his late brother) to the highly emotional ending (the funeral train & his night burial at Arlington) this documentary takes you on a journey & shows you how Bobby grew through experience.
<br />
<br />Tightly edited, the documentary includes some rare clips of RFK that I hadn't seen before, including his appearance on 'Meet the Press', where conflicted about whether to run for president against LBJ he talks about 'getting off the planet' to one of the questioning presenters (can you imagine a politician saying something as existentialist as that nowadays!)
<br />
<br />The interviewees, a mix of historians and RFK's staff and friends are good value with some insightful comments.
<br />
<br />For those new to Bobby and wishing to learn more this is an excellent introduction to his life, with a good overview about the social upheavals of America in the 1960s as well.
<br />
<br />For RFK fans the film doesn't really tell you anything you hadn't know before, but the narrative thrust of the programme is so compelling that it almost doesn't matter.
<br />
<br />Of course, two hours to cover the very full and complex life of RFK is really not enough. The documentary is very tightly edited and if there is a fault, it doesn't have nearly enough clips from Bobby's speeches. 
<br />
<br />Another hour would have added more depth to the story. Too many things are missed out - RFK's visit to South Africa in 1966 and his anti-apartheid speech;his fight for the rights of Native Americans.
<br />
<br />Overall, an excellent addition to the growing numbers of documentaries on Robert Kennedy. 
<br />
<br />I defy anyone not to shed a tear and wonder what might have been at the conclusion of this excellent and worthwhile documentary.
<br /></span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Definitive portrait of Robert Kennedy</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>3</span>
                      /
                      <span>3</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2004-10-18</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>I have read just about every book and watched just about every movie that there is regarding Robert Kennedy, and I've got to say that this is, by far, one of the best pieces of work I've yet to see.  The movie was brilliantly put together in a way which captures the audience's attention, allows for us to actually *feel* what Robert Kennedy is feeling, to sense the tension during chaotic times, and most importantly, to understand the wonderful man who made a huge difference for America.
<br />
<br />This movie is extremely well-balanced, provides excellent insight to the inner mind/heart of Robert Kennedy, and includes many very personal excerpts either via interview or editing of films from Kennedy's life.  
<br />
<br />If you are looking to pick one movie on Robert Kennedy - this is it.  This is THE one you want to watch.  After watching this, you will see Robert Kennedy in a way you never have before.
<br />
<br /></span>
                  
              
